25|$|Black pepper is {{produced}} from the still-green, unripe <b>drupes</b> of the pepper plant. The <b>drupes</b> are cooked briefly in hot water, both to clean {{them and to}} prepare them for drying. The heat ruptures cell walls in the pepper, speeding the work of browning enzymes during drying. The <b>drupes</b> dry in the sun or by machine for several days, during which the pepper around the seed shrinks and darkens into a thin, wrinkled black layer. Once dry, the spice is called black peppercorn. On some estates, the berries are separated from the stem by hand and then sun-dried without the boiling process.|$|R
