50|$|In Spain, pacharán {{is made by}} soaking sloe <b>drupes</b> in an anise-flavoured spirit, {{resulting}} in a light reddish-brown, sweet liquid, around 25-30% alcohol by volume. In Italy, bargnolino is made by soaking sloe <b>drupes</b> with sugar and spices in spirit alcohol (recipe varies locally), resulting a reddish, sweet liquor, around 40-45% alcohol by volume; it is often chilled before serving.|$|R
50|$|Some species {{formerly}} {{recognized in}} Rhus, such as poison ivy (Toxicodendron radicans, syn. Rhus toxicodendron), poison oak (Toxicodendron diversilobum, syn. Rhus diversiloba) and poison sumac (Toxicodendron vernix, syn. Rhus vernix), have the allergen urushiol {{and can cause}} severe allergic reactions. Poison sumac may be identified by its white <b>drupes,</b> which are {{quite different from the}} red <b>drupes</b> of true Rhus species.|$|R
